---
import ArticleLayout from '../../layouts/ArticleLayout.astro';

const pageUrl = 'https://aipedia.wiki/about/editor/';
const pageName = 'Eli Marsh, Editor-in-Chief - aipedia.wiki';
const pageDesc = 'Meet Eli Marsh, editor of aipedia.wiki. Former backend dev turned full-time AI tools reviewer. 200+ tools tested, 132 published reviews, 280+ head-to-head comparisons.';

const personLD = JSON.stringify({
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Person',
  name: 'Eli Marsh',
  jobTitle: 'Editor-in-Chief',
  url: pageUrl,
  worksFor: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'aipedia.wiki',
    url: 'https://aipedia.wiki',
  },
  knowsAbout: [
    'Artificial Intelligence',
    'AI Tools',
    'Software Engineering',
    'Product Evaluation',
    'Technical Writing',
  ],
  sameAs: [],
});

const credentials = [
  { value: '200+', label: 'Tools tested since 2023' },
  { value: '132', label: 'Published reviews' },
  { value: '280+', label: 'Comparisons' },
  { value: '14', label: 'Categories' },
];
---

<ArticleLayout
  title="Editor-in-Chief"
  seoTitle={pageName}
  description={pageDesc}
  breadcrumbs={[{ label: 'About', href: '/about/' }, { label: 'Editor' }]}
>
  <Fragment slot="default">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={personLD} />
  </Fragment>

  <!-- Header card -->
  <div class="not-prose bg-[var(--bg-card)] border border-[var(--border)] rounded-xl p-6 md:p-8 my-6">
    <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row items-start gap-6">
      <img
        src="/editor-headshot.jpg"
        alt="Eli Marsh, Editor-in-Chief of aipedia.wiki"
        width="80"
        height="80"
        class="shrink-0 w-20 h-20 rounded-full object-cover border-2 border-[rgba(167,139,250,0.25)]"
        loading="eager"
      />
      <div class="min-w-0 flex-1">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-[var(--text-primary)] m-0">Eli Marsh</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-[var(--accent-primary)] font-medium mt-1 mb-3">Editor-in-Chief, aipedia.wiki</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] leading-relaxed m-0">
          Former backend dev. Now I test AI tools full-time and tell you which ones are actually worth paying for.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Credentials strip -->
  <div class="not-prose grid grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-4 gap-3 my-8">
    {credentials.map((c) => (
      <div class="bg-[var(--bg-card)] border border-[var(--border)] rounded-lg px-4 py-3 text-center">
        <div class="text-xl font-semibold text-[var(--text-primary)] leading-none">{c.value}</div>
        <div class="text-[11px] text-[var(--text-muted)] uppercase tracking-[0.12em] mt-1.5">{c.label}</div>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <!-- Bio -->
  <h2>How this started</h2>

  <p>
    I kept a Notion doc. That's the honest origin story. In late 2022 I was a backend developer at a B2B SaaS company in Wellington, and I started using the GPT-3 API for internal tooling. Then GPT-4 dropped, and suddenly every week there was a new AI tool claiming to be the best at something. I needed a way to keep track of what actually worked.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Notion doc became a spreadsheet. The spreadsheet got a scoring system. By late 2023 I had tested over 80 tools and the doc was 40 pages long, so I put it on the web. The thesis was simple: every AI tools directory I could find ranked tools by whoever paid the most affiliate commission, not by whether they were any good. I wanted a reference I could trust, so I built one.
  </p>

  <p>
    I quit the day job in mid-2025. The site earns enough through affiliate links to keep the lights on, but commissions have zero influence on scores. If a tool pays 30% commission and scores a 4/10, it gets a 4/10. The Dead Tools section exists because pretending failures didn't happen is dishonest, and I've always found the failures more interesting than the successes anyway.
  </p>

  <h2>How I test</h2>

  <p>
    I use every tool I review whenever possible. For coding tools that means running real tasks through them, not synthetic benchmarks. For writing tools it means feeding them the kind of prompts real users actually type, not cherry-picked demos. For image and video generators it means running the same prompt across multiple tools and comparing the outputs side by side.
  </p>

  <p>
    When I can't directly test (enterprise tiers, tools with waitlists, tools limited to specific regions), the review says so. I don't pretend to have hands-on experience I don't have. In those cases the review is built from primary sources: official docs, changelogs, pricing pages, and credible third-party evaluations.
  </p>

  <p>
    The site runs on a verification pipeline I built with Claude Code. Every price, flagship model version, and status claim is checked against live sources on a recurring schedule. If Midjourney raises its prices on a Tuesday, the tool page should reflect that by Wednesday. That's the goal; sometimes it takes a few days longer, but every page shows when it was last verified so you can judge for yourself.
  </p>

  <!-- How I Score -->
  <h2>How I score</h2>

  <div class="not-prose bg-[var(--bg-card)] border border-[var(--border)] rounded-xl p-6 my-6">
    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] leading-relaxed m-0 mb-4">
      Four dimensions, each scored 1 to 10: <strong class="text-[var(--text-primary)]">Utility</strong> (does the core job well), <strong class="text-[var(--text-primary)]">Value</strong> (quality per dollar), <strong class="text-[var(--text-primary)]">Moat</strong> (hard to replicate or displace), and <strong class="text-[var(--text-primary)]">Longevity</strong> (will it exist in two years). The overall score is the unweighted average. Scores are not inflated. A 7 means genuinely good. A 5 means average. I've never given a 10 because nothing is perfect.
    </p>
    <a
      href="/about/scoring/"
      class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 bg-[var(--accent-primary)] text-white px-5 py-2.5 rounded-lg text-sm font-medium no-underline hover:opacity-90 transition-opacity"
    >
      Full scoring methodology
      <span>-></span>
    </a>
  </div>

  <!-- What I actually use -->
  <h2>What I use daily</h2>

  <p>
    People always ask, so here it is. My daily stack as of April 2026:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><a href="/tools/claude-code/">Claude Code</a> for anything that touches code. I run it from the terminal for most of my development work on this site.</li>
    <li><a href="/tools/cursor/">Cursor</a> when I want an IDE. Multi-file editing is better in a GUI sometimes.</li>
    <li><a href="/tools/perplexity/">Perplexity</a> for research. I use it to verify pricing and feature claims across the catalog.</li>
    <li><a href="/tools/claude/">Claude</a> (Opus 4.6) for writing and analysis. Most of the editorial decisions on this site go through a conversation with Claude first.</li>
    <li><a href="/tools/suno/">Suno</a> for making terrible AI music when I need a break. Would never recommend it for professional use, but it's fun.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- Editorial stance -->
  <h2>Things I believe</h2>

  <div class="not-prose grid gap-3 my-6">
    {[
      {
        title: 'Open weights matter more than benchmarks',
        body: 'A model you can run locally and fine-tune will always beat a marginally better model locked behind an API that could change terms tomorrow.',
      },
      {
        title: 'If you hide pricing, you know it\'s too high',
        body: 'Any tool that makes you "Contact Sales" to see a price is banking on sunk-cost fallacy during the demo. I flag this on every tool page where it applies.',
      },
      {
        title: 'The best AI tool is the one you actually use',
        body: 'I\'ve seen people agonize over ChatGPT vs Claude for weeks while getting nothing done. Pick one, learn it properly, switch later if you need to.',
      },
      {
        title: 'Every ChatGPT wrapper should say so',
        body: 'If your "AI-powered" feature is a thin layer over the OpenAI API, be honest about it. Users deserve to know what they\'re paying a markup for.',
      },
    ].map((item) => (
      <div class="flex gap-4 bg-[var(--bg-card)] border border-[var(--border)] rounded-lg p-5">
        <div class="shrink-0 w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-[rgba(167,139,250,0.12)] text-[var(--accent-primary)] flex items-center justify-center text-sm">
          &#10003;
        </div>
        <div class="min-w-0">
          <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--text-primary)] m-0 mb-1">{item.title}</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] leading-relaxed m-0">{item.body}</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <!-- Contact & Corrections -->
  <div
    id="contact"
    class="not-prose mt-14 bg-gradient-to-br from-[rgba(167,139,250,0.08)] to-[rgba(96,165,250,0.06)] border border-[rgba(167,139,250,0.25)] rounded-xl p-8 scroll-mt-24"
  >
    <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
      <div class="shrink-0 w-10 h-10 rounded-full bg-[rgba(167,139,250,0.15)] text-[var(--accent-primary)] flex items-center justify-center text-lg">
        &#9998;
      </div>
      <div class="min-w-0 flex-1">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[var(--text-primary)] m-0 mb-2">Corrections and contact</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] leading-relaxed m-0 mb-3">
          Found a wrong price, a changed feature, or a tool that shut down? I read every correction and update pages when the evidence checks out. If you think a score is unfair, tell me what you've used the tool for, what you'd score it, and why. I'll look at it.
        </p>
        <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3 mt-5">
          <a
            href="mailto:eli@aipedia.wiki?subject=Correction%20or%20feedback"
            class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 bg-[var(--accent-primary)] text-white px-5 py-2.5 rounded-lg text-sm font-medium no-underline hover:opacity-90 transition-opacity"
          >
            <span>Email me</span>
            <span>-></span>
          </a>
          <a
            href="/about/"
            class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 border border-[var(--border)] text-[var(--text-secondary)] hover:text-[var(--text-primary)] px-5 py-2.5 rounded-lg text-sm font-medium no-underline transition-colors"
          >
            About aipedia.wiki
          </a>
          <a
            href="/about/scoring/"
            class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 border border-[var(--border)] text-[var(--text-secondary)] hover:text-[var(--text-primary)] px-5 py-2.5 rounded-lg text-sm font-medium no-underline transition-colors"
          >
            Scoring methodology
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

</ArticleLayout>
